1. Load Datasets and Data Manipulation¶

We used several datasets in this project, including a route dataset, an airport dataset, and passenger data from ORD, ATL, DEN, and DFW airports (both originating from and departing to).

In the code below, we will perform data manipulation techniques to combine these datasets into two dataframes: us_routes_df and passengers_df.

2. Network Analysis¶

Our team used different centrality metrics including degree centrality,betweenness centrality, closeness centrality, eigenvector centrality and pagerank. It turns out that the top 4 airports are:

  • ATL (Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport)
  • ORD (Chicago O'Hare International Airport)
  • DEN (Denver International Airport)
  • DFW (Dallas Fort Worth International Airport)

# decomposition for seasonality

def sea_decomp(data):

    seasonal_data = pd.DataFrame(index=data.index)
    for country in data.columns:
        result = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(data[country], model='additive')
        seasonal_data[country] = result.seasonal
    
    return seasonal_data

decom = sea_decomp(df_clean)

# euclidean distance
def calc_euclidean_dist(data):

    c_num = len(data.columns)
    distances = np.zeros((c_num, c_num))

    for i in range(c_num):
        for j in range(i, c_num):
            c1 = data.columns[i]
            c2 = data.columns[j]
            dist = np.linalg.norm(data[c1] - data[c2])
            distances[i, j] = dist
            distances[j, i] = dist  

    c_name = data.columns
    distance_df = pd.DataFrame(distances, index=c_name, columns=c_name)

    return distance_df

euclidean_distances = calc_euclidean_dist(df_clean)

# cosine distance
def calc_cos_sim(data):

    c_num = len(data.columns)
    similarities = np.zeros((c_num, c_num))

    for i in range(c_num):
        for j in range(i, c_num):
            c1 = data.columns[i]
            c2 = data.columns[j]
            s1 = data[c1]
            s2 = data[c2]
            similarity = np.dot(s1, s2) / (np.linalg.norm(s1) * np.linalg.norm(s2))
            similarities[i, j] = similarity
            similarities[j, i] = similarity  

    country_names = data.columns
    similarity_df = pd.DataFrame(similarities, index=country_names, columns=country_names)

    return similarity_df

cosine_similarities = calc_cos_sim(df_clean)

# dtw distance
import numpy as np
def calc_pairwise_dtw_cost(x, y, ret_matrix=False):
    n = len(x)
    m = len(y)
    cost_matrix = np.zeros((n, m))
    cost_matrix[0, 0] = (x[0] - y[0]) ** 2   
    for i in range(1, n):
        cost_matrix[i, 0] = cost_matrix[i-1, 0] + (x[i] - y[0]) ** 2
    for j in range(1, m):
        cost_matrix[0, j] = cost_matrix[0, j-1] + (x[0] - y[j]) ** 2
    for i in range(1, n):
        for j in range(1, m):
            cost_matrix[i, j] = (x[i] - y[j]) ** 2 + min(cost_matrix[i-1, j], cost_matrix[i, j-1], cost_matrix[i-1, j-1])
    if ret_matrix:
        return cost_matrix
    else:
        return cost_matrix[-1, -1]
    
def calc_dtw_cost(df):
    df_dtw = pd.DataFrame(index=df.columns, columns=df.columns)
    for country1 in df.columns:
        for country2 in df.columns:
            dtw_cost = calc_pairwise_dtw_cost(df[country1], df[country2])
            df_dtw.loc[country1, country2] = dtw_cost
    return df_dtw


dtw_cost_df = calc_dtw_cost(df_clean)
